ANTHRAX - INDIA (23): (ASSAM) BUFFALO, NOT
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 17 Aug 2016 06.39 PM IST
Source: Times of India, Times News Network (TNN)
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/guwahati/Test-says-Kaziranga-buffaloes-did-not-die-of-anthrax/articleshow/53741658.cms


The Kaziranga National Park (KNP) authorities breathed sigh of relief after test confirmed that the 7 Asiatic wild buffaloes did not die of anthrax infection. Kaziranga divisional forest officer, Suvasish Das said that the final test on the samples of 7 carcasses showed negative result for anthrax. Das said that tests were done at the College of Veterinary Science (CVS) and Animal Research Laboratory (ARL). "We received confirmation from CVS and ARL that the samples from carcasses of seven buffaloes were tested negative for anthrax," Das said.

Kaziranga, a World Heritage Site about 250 km [about 155 mi] from here [Guwahati], has over 1000 Asiatic wild buffaloes besides rhinos, elephants, tigers, eastern swamp deer, among other wildlife life in 430 sq km [about 166 sq mi] area'.

Seven Asiatic wildlife buffaloes were found death on [10 Aug 2016], prompting the park officials to send samples from the carcasses to CVS for ascertaining the cause of deaths.

A preliminary test, however, indicated that the cause of death might be due to anthrax. "That is why we waited for the final test which takes at least 5 days to culture the anthrax bacteria. Now that the test showed negative to anthrax, we are relieved," a park official said. Given the fact that in 1955 there was a "sporadic" death of Asiatic wild buffaloes due to anthrax infection, park officials said that this time the 7 animals were disposed in adherence to all the standard precautionary measures, even before the final test results. "We used chemical treatments, as well as incineration of the carcasses, before burying all the remains according to the prescribed safety measures," the official added.

Das said that the tests for ascertaining the [actual] cause of deaths of 7 buffaloes are still on.

Kaziranga suffered a large-scale loss of wildlife in the flood last month [July 2016]. Over 300 different species of animals, including 22 rhinos were killed during the flood, one of the worst deluge the park experienced in last five years.

[Byline: Naresh Mitra|]

