Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The park officials made absolutely the correct decision to properly dispose of the carcasses by disinfection with formalin, incineration, and burial. And they also had 2 diagnostic labs cross check each other. Over the years I have acquired some experience, personal, direct, and indirect, with this pathogen and it regularly surprises me how sometimes even very competent laboratories can miss seeing it. So take 2 samples and use a 2nd lab if you doubt the first's findings.

With stains off the shelf there is a 20 percent chance of a false positive when reading stained blood smears. Better to use Michael Owen's M'Fadyean stain; see Michael P Owen, et al: A simple, reliable M'Fadyean stain for visualizing the _Bacillus anthracis_ capsule. J Microbiol Methods. 2013; 92(3): 264-9
http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167701213000134. - Mod.MHJ

The Asian buffalo (_Bubalus arnee_) is a large bovine native to the Indian subcontinent and Southeast Asia. It is considered endangered, and their populations have declined by around 50 percent in the last decades. The most important threats include interbreeding with feral and domestic buffalo in and around protected areas; poaching; habitat loss; invasive species; disease and parasites transmitted by domestic livestock (such as, tuberculosis, brucellosis, foot and mouth disease, etc.), and competition with domestic livestock. - Mod.PMB

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4425093,9854.]
